project_info.prj_title: Erosion Reduction at Hayes Road Stream Crossing
project_info.prj_overview: The project is located on Hayes Road in the Town of Duxbury in the Crossett Brook subwatershed. The crossing was washed out during a storm event in May 2011. Due to confusion at the time, the adjacent landowner replaced the structure with a poorly built, under sized culvert. A 35-foot long metal tank culvert conveys Crossett Brook under the roadway. The shape of the culvert is now distorted with sagging and buckling of the roof under the roadway. The project was initially identified as a fish passage issue. Considerable work has been done to determine the type of structure needed to accommodate fish passage as well as achieve geomorphic stability. Data collection in 2014 included channel cross sections upstream and downstream of the structure, channel profile, existing dimensions of the culvert, road elevations, and other site features. Borings were also taken to inform the type of structure best suited for the site along with hydrologic and hydraulic analyses. The recommended replacement structure is an open bottom arch. Project is considered to constitute a watershed based plan implementation effort in light of Winooski River basin plan (2012) and BMP scenario tool associated with Lake Champlain TMDL being developed by EPA-Region 1.

The Town of Waitsfield is proposing to build a new Town Office on a 0.85 acre undeveloped, Town-owned site at 4144 Main Street in historic Waitsfield Village. The building, paved driveway and parking area, and concrete sidewalks will create approximately 13,555 square feet of new impermeable surfaces that will increase the volume of stormwater. The project includes construction of four rain gardens and a sitting garden to capture and treat the resulting stormwater (see site plan). The project is fully designed and was put out to bid for construction but the low bid came in substantially higher than the funds available, which requires locating additional money or removing elements from the plan. If the rain gardens are eliminated, stormwater would be directed to an existing storm drain system that drains directly into the Mad River.

project_info.prj_title: Enhancing Nutrient Management Plan Implementation with GoCrop Software
project_info.prj_overview:
The goal of this project is to enhance goCrop to provide farmers with better NMP planning and implementation tools that will help them meet regulations and improve crop and environmental quality. The goCrop system is available to any farm, consultant or state/federal employee that wants to access/use this system for NMP development. However, our primary focus and users are located in the Lake Champlain Basin. Currently standards require the 129 MFOs and 25 LFOs in Vermont to have nutrient management plans (NMPs) that meet the USDA NRCS 590 Standard. If the Bill on Water Quality (S.49) passes as it currently stands, the number of required small farm certifications with nutrient management plans will increase five fold to include 726 small farms as well. GoCrop is an easy to use, affordable, and accessible tool for creating a NMP and recording management activities. Currently over 150 farmers have used goCrop to develop a NMP for their farm. Funds for this project will expand the capacity to develop NMPs for small farms and provide essential enhancements to further improve the implementation of NMPs on large and medium farms.
In the beginning of 2015, specific improvements and additions to GoCrop were identified with current farm users and state/federal staff throughout the state of Vermont. Improvements include a more flexible interface and expansion of stored data. As an example, with enhancements farmers would be able to monitor soil test phosphorus levels across years or track p-index changes over time. There are also several planned new features for GoCrop. First a mapping component will provide farmers with a visual representation of their fields, incorporate various map layers (including CLUs, soils, Nitrogen Leach Index, and others), and geolocate the field a farmer is in. A grazing tool will build on the mapping component to include grazing planning tools that manage feed and nutrient deposition from animals. This is a segment of NMPs that has been ignored by nutrient planners and many farmers. Furthermore, an ability to record weather data at any time will help GoCrop meet reporting standards. During the duration of this project we expect to work with at least 60 farmers (existing and new users) to develop and beta-test the goCrop enhancements.
Currently, GoCrop is limited by funding in how many new capabilities can be incorporated into the existing framework. Recording AAPs or RAPs and sending reports to state agencies is another service GoCrop can provide. These additions to GoCrop will increase the functionality of GoCrop to be useful to more farmers, providing one place for a farmer to update farm details, store management history, enter current records, create an NMP, and record AAPs/RAPs.

project_info.prj_title: Winooski Trees for Streams/Riparian Buffer Restoration, 2016
project_info.prj_overview:
The Grantees Trees for Streams (TFS) program was created from a model program started by the Lamoille Conservation District and has been managed since 1999 in the Winooski District to enhance riparian buffers on private lands throughout Vermont. The Grantee proposes to plant four acres of riparian buffer along 2,955 linear feet across six properties:
1. Essex High School: 2 Educational Drive, Essex Junction, Indian Brook, Segment M11, 2.3 acres (35+ buffer) 2. Hunter: 428 Bolton Valley Access Road, Bolton, Joiner Brook Segment R10.S3.02, .3 acres (35 buffer) 3. Allard: 467 W. Milton Rd., Milton, Lamoille River Segment R01, .4 acres (35 buffer) 4. Albert: 6308 Shelburne Road, Shelburne, McCabe Brook Segment T1.05, .25 acres (35 buffer) 5. OHara: 113 Ethan Allen Roan, Jericho, Lee River, T4.03S2.01, .25 acres (35 buffer) 6. Bedard: 1215 Main Rd., Huntington, Huntington River Segment M09, .5 acres (35 +buffer)
Each planting site has been visited with US Fish and Wildlife Service partners to confirm stability for planting. Planting plans will be designed to include native tree and shrub species that are appropriate for the site based on the soils and natural plant community identified through site visits.
The Grantee will execute a maintenance agreement with landowner(s) of all treatment site(s) protecting the buffer plantings for at least 10 years. The agreement must allow for Grantee site access, with advance notice, to periodically inspect plantings. The Grantee will also develop a stewardship plan covering the establishment period for the plantings of at least three years.

project_info.prj_overview: River corridor conservation easement along the Gihon River on approximately 12.8 acres on the Rankin farm in Johnson, Vermont. Objective is to allow for passive restoration of this stretch of the Gihon River to return to its least erosive condition. Method will involve working with landowner to enter into a permanent conservation easement and completing buffer plantings on 2.9 acres. As part of the implementation of river corridor easement project, a USDA Conservation Reserve Enhancement Program (CREP) buffer consisting of 50 feet from the top of the river bank, and totaling 2.9 acres, will be established and maintained (planting scheduled for Spring 2017).

project_info.prj_title: Kaiser Farm River Corridor Easement Purchase
project_info.prj_overview: The Kaiser Farm is located in Stowe's Nebraska Valley and is bisected by Miller Brook. The Grantee and Stowe Land Trust are working together to purchase a conservation easement on 49-acres of the farm, enabling a simultaneous transfer to new farm owners. The Vermont Housing & Conservation Board has approved a grant to assist in the acquisition of a conservation easement on the 49-acre property, and Stowe Land Trust is launching a local fundraising effort with a total budget of $354,000. To maximize the conservation outcomes in this conservation project, the partners would like to incorporate a river corridor easement and buffer. This larger effort to conserve the Kaiser farm and facilitate and transfer to a farmer is helping to make a river corridor easement possible. The Kaiser property is bounded by Mount Mansfield State Forest on two sides and abuts land previously conserved by Stowe Land Trust to the north. The property has 3,200 feet of frontage on two sides of Miller Brook. The area along the Brook has been enrolled in the Conservation Reserve Enhancement Program (CREP), and a river corridor easement will help to secure the positive outcomes of this past investment. The Grantee will secure a river corridor easement including a 50-foot forested buffer within the river corridor. The buffer will reduce or eliminate water-quality impacts from the farmland and forestland abutting the brook, and provide shading, wildlife habitat, and soil-stabilizing roots and roughness to an otherwise open area.

VACD will use grant funds to support riparian and shoreline buffer plantings on approximately 30 sites totaling 20 acres each year over a two year period. The Trees for Streams (TFS) program is implemented on a state-wide basis in a collaborative effort between VACD and Vermonts 14 Natural Resources Conservation Districts (NRCDs). This proposal is a continuation of the state-wide VACD TFS program which began with ERP support in 2014 and is continuing with ERP support in 2015. The TFS concept was initiated by Lamoille Conservation District 16 years ago and has become a signature program of NRCDs. The purpose of TFS is to improve and protect water quality by planting riparian buffers in high-priority watersheds. The installation of vegetated buffers is a widely supported practice with a number of critical benefits to water quality, riparian habitat, and overall river health and geomorphic conditions. Buffers filter runoff and NPS pollution from adjacent land use, offer increased root mass to enhance floodplain function and the attenuation of floodwaters, and enhance habitat by providing needed cover and shade to a variety of riparian and aquatic species. In addition to supporting buffer plantings, as in our 2015 ERP program, this proposal provides a small amount of funding to conservation districts ($1,000 per district per year) to identify projects and begin developing working relationships with landowners for implementation the following year. Project is considered to constitute a watershed based plan implementation effort in light of various completed and ANR-approved river basin water quality plans each of which give high priority to riparian plantings and for sites within Lake Champlain basin and the BMP scenario tool associated with Lake Champlain TMDL being developed by EPA-Region 1.

project_info.prj_overview: Central Vermont Regional Planning Commission has been helping the Village of Northfield map its stormwater systems since 2011. In 2013, CVRPC was awarded an ERP grant to identify and design stormwater structures in the Village of Northfield using the mapping and reports that CVRPC had previously completed. Then in 2014 CVRPC was awarded a construction grant to install one of the smaller designed stormwater sites on Central St. This 2016 ERP project is the next step to construct one of the larger identified and designed stormwater sites. The site that has been selected is behind the Village Green in Northfield. This site has local support from the Town of Northfield Manager and Utilities Superintendent. Once completed, the Village Green site will utilize a large end-of-pipe bioretention basin which could capture surface runoff from 14 acres of the downtown. Project is considered to constitute a watershed based plan implementation effort in light of Winooski River basin plan (2012) and BMP scenario tool associated with Lake Champlain TMDL being developed by EPA-Region 1.

This project involves working with multiple landowners in the Lake Champlain basin to restore riparian buffers by planting native trees and shrubs. Planting native trees and shrubs along river corridors reduces phosphorus and sediment loading that can impact local waterways and Lake Champlain. Riparian areas along streams protect water quality by filtering out pollutants and excessive nutrients such as phosphorus, nitrogen, and sediment. In addition, riparian buffers help to stabilize stream banks, which can prevent the loss of land through erosion. Forested riparian buffers improve habitat for fish, birds, and other wildlife by keeping water temperatures cool and providing important forage and cover. Under this project, the Winooski Natural Resources Conservation District partnered with the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service to assist cooperating landowners in restoring and protecting fish and wildlife habitat on their property.

In partnership with Vermonts regional planning commissions, the Clean Water Initiative Program is offering aid to municipalities in implementing best management practices on municipal roads to improve water quality. Practices eligible for funding under this project include drainage ditch installation and upgrades, turnouts, removal of high road shoulders, and stabilization of drainage culverts and catch basin outlets, and on Class 4 roads, stabilization of gully erosion. Projects must target sections of roads that are hydrologically-connected road segments that are next to or cross streams, wetlands, lakes, or ponds.

project_info.prj_title: Fuller Hill Road, Warren Stormwater Treatment Implementation
project_info.prj_overview: As part of continued efforts from the assessment and design grants, the Town of Warren will improve stormwater management on the lower reaches of Fuller Hill Road, a rural residential road which is unpaved and contributing significant sedimentation and stormwater flow into the Mad River.

project_info.prj_title: Packard Road, Jericho Stormwater Treatment Implementation
project_info.prj_overview: A large infiltration basin installation on a Town-owned parcel to decrease stormwater flow and mitigate flooding located on the corner of Packard Road and VT-15. A large area drains to this location and contributes to annual, seasonal flooding. During times of high flow, stormwater is piped to the Browns River. This project helps to mitigate flooding and decrease stormwater flow to the river by detaining runoff and promoting infiltration.

project_info.prj_title: River Corridor Easement- Lewis Creek- Briggs
project_info.prj_overview: This river corridor easement is located along the Lewis Creek in Starksboro VT. The easement protects 37 acres of land on the Briggs property. No additional BMPs will be added except the protection of this land.

project_info.prj_title: River Corridor Easement Grant- Lewis Creek, Clifford
project_info.prj_overview: This river corridor easement is located along the Lewis Creek in Starksboro VT. The easement restores river channel and floodplain to meet fluvial geomorphic equilibrium conditions by protecting 31 acres of land on the Clifford property.

The goal of this project is to remove Mill Pond Dam, an unused and failing structure, from Indian Brook in Colchester. The dam was inspected by DEC Dam Safety in 2011, and was found to be in poor condition. It blocks aquatic organism passage through this reach, disrupts downstream sediment transport and impounds approximately 34,000 cubic yards of sediment. This project will eliminate the barrier, restore sediment transport, and remove approximately 25,000 cubic yards of impounded sediment. The sediment to be removed contains approximately 14 tons of phosphorus.

project_info.prj_title: Warren School Campus Stormwater Management - Subsurface Chambers
project_info.prj_overview: The project consists of installing underground infiltration chambers to capture and infiltrate stormwater underneath the Warren Elementary School parking lot. The chambers are able to infiltrate up to the one year, 24 hour storm, reducing the number of events that activate that outlet significantly. The project also involves installing a bioretention/Rain Garden that collects a large amount of runoff form the school campus and the school roofs and parking lots.

This project is an equipment purchase of a grader-mounted compactor for the Town of Stowe, which will improve water quality by "sealing" and compacting a freshly graded gravel road which will make the surface far less vulnerable to erosion from both precipitation and vehicular traffic.

An existing large 4 foot concrete culvert about 60 feet long is eroding on the downstream end and two sections have fallen off. The goal is to install the proper sized structure and prevent the ongoing discharge and reduce the risk to the road. The embedment of the structure will need to remain and some protection at the inlet end may be warranted to prevent a head-cut from progressing upstream.

project_info.prj_overview: This project restores over 10 acres of floodplain along the Cold River in the Town of Clarendon, which is currently cut off by a large berm. The site is located between Route 7, where it was destroyed during Tropical Storm Irene, and the Middle Road on the right bank. This project was identified as a top priority through the river corridor planning process.

project_info.prj_overview: The stormwater retrofit practice is a system of sub-surface infiltration chambers supplied by ADS-StormTech with an infiltration basin on top of the chambers. The chambers will treat runoff collected in the Schools stormwater system (catch basins, roof drains, etc.) while the infiltration basin will collect surface runoff from a large portion of the Schools parking lot. All runoff will infiltrate up to the Channel Protection volume (CPv).

project_info.prj_title: Bouchard Farm Ditch Improvement Project- Rock River
project_info.prj_overview: This project reconstructs an existing, standard channelized ditch into a two-stage system that will reduce out-of-channel stream flow velocities. This will allow sediments to deposit in the bench while reducing bank erosion within the reach. In turn, this will also reduce downstream peak flooding by increased flood storage capacity of the two-stage ditch. Floodplain is restored to 2500 feet of ditched stream on farmland.

This project improves two drainage structures and positively impact 9,365 linear feet of road drainage on the Towle Neighborhood Road, located in Franklin, Vermont. This road crosses headwater tributaries to the Marsh Brook. Currently, there are two culverts where the road embankment above the culverts are severely eroding into the stream because the culverts are too short and lack the necessary erosion prevention measures. The outcome of the project includes installing headwalls at the inlets to both culverts, and providing rock-lined splash pools at both culvert outlets.

project_info.prj_title: Hathaway Point Agricultural Stormwater Runoff Project
project_info.prj_overview: This project constructs a stormwater management system including a detention basin and sand filter swale with check dams to control agricultural stormwater runoff. Agricultural stormwater runoff from the Montagne farm has periodically exceeded the capacity of a shallow swale system and inundated neighboring residential properties. This project includes re-routing three agricultural swales in order to reduce flood risk to neighboring parcels and improve water quality of stormwater leaving the farm.

project_info.prj_title: Waterman Brook Culvert to Bridge Project - Johnson
project_info.prj_overview: This project is located on the French Hill Block of Mt Mansfield State Forest in Johnson. The grantee will replace a large (5) culvert on the Forest Road that crosses Boulley Brook just above Waterman Brook. The current structure is an old oil tank which has been in place for some time. It will be replaced with a 12" bridge. This will prevent road failure/sedimentation on a State Forest Highway, significantly upgrade the stream crossing, and provide a demonstration site for communities and forest landowners on improved crossings for stream corridor management.

project_info.prj_title: Bombardier Forest Road- Preston Brook logging road remediation
project_info.prj_overview: The Bombardier Road is located on the east side of the brook and is part of Camel's Hump State Park. It is used as a logging road by the Department of Forest Parks and Recreation as well as a ski trail. In its present state, it does not meet Accepted Management Practice standards for logging roads. The forest road and log landing are adding stormwater runoff to areas of landslides on Preston Brook. This project would bring the road into compliance with standards, and in turn, lessen the stormwater impacts to Preston Brook.

project_info.prj_title: Derby, Morgan and Brownington shared Hydroseeder program
project_info.prj_overview: The project will manage a 3-town (Derby, Morgan and Brownington) collaborative Hydroseeder Program. This program will promote and accelerate the use of vegetation stabilization for roadside ditching and steep side slopes by purchasing a hydroseeder and one year's supply of materials to be shared by the Vermont towns of Derby, Brownington, and Morgan. These three towns are all in the Lake Memphremagog watershed basin.

This project proposes to stabilize an outfall and repair gully erosion caused by high flow stormwater inputs draining a large watershed. Mitigation will include filling and stabilizing the gully and creating an armored step pool system to treat stormwater before it is discharged into the Stevens Branch. There is some urgency to this project as the gully continues to erode increasing the potential cost to implement.

project_info.prj_overview: This project involves the implementation of stormwater treatment/erosion control practices at the Franklin Town Highway Garage. This project was identified in the Franklin Stormwater Plan. There is a catch basin on site that is overwhelmed by sediment coming from the highway lot causing the system to not work properly. Sediment is also running off onto two other properties surrounding the town highway lot. This project implements multiple stormwater treatment practices at the Franklin Town Garage and adjacent public parking lot.

This project installs a treatment practice along the edge of the paved area with a stable outlet overflow to the existing catchbasin on High Street. Half of the large paved lot and all of the gravel lot drain to a stone lined ditch along the steep entrance ramp to a vegetated swale along High Street. The swale will be improved to increase water storage to improve infiltration and sediment retention.

Currently, stormwater runoff from agricultural fields and private land drains into highly erodible soils causing significant gully erosion into the West Branch of the New Haven River in the town of Bristol. Water quality monitoring conducted at this location has documented high turbidity, total suspended solids, and sedimentation in the West Branch. This project stabilizes the gully to prevent further erosion at this location.

This project implements stormwater retrofit systems designed to capture, detain and treat a portion of the water quality storm volume from existing impervious surfaces on the south side of the school. Selected practices include rain gardens, tree plantings, bioretention, and infiltration trench. Approximately 58% of the 4.9 acre drainage area and 74% of the 2.8 acres of impervious surfaces are routed through an existing or proposed treatment practice.

This project provides state-funded cost-share to restore and protect 182-acre wetland with high ecological value on private property in Salisbury, VT. The project partners with the U.S. Department of Agriculture as part of an NRCS Wetland Reserve Easement (WRE).

This project involves the design and construction of a stormwater infiltration basin to treat flow from the York Street drainage prior to discharge in the Poultney River. As designed, the system will collect and treat stormwater from over half of the developed Poultney Village area. The intent of the new stormwater treatment structure is to maximize diversion and treatment of the flow. The stormwater treatment basin is sized for a best fit Water Quality Volume of 1.6 acre-feet and effectively treats runoff from 35.6 acres of impervious surface by retaining 831,791 gallons of stormwater. It is anticipated that the basin can achieve 94 percent total phosphorus removal, resulting in a phosphorus reduction of 85 pounds of phosphorus per year from Lake Champlain (consultant-provided estimate, to be verified).

project_info.prj_title: Precision Manure Management in the Jewett Brook Watershed
project_info.prj_overview: UVM will provide equipment and technical assistance with the installation of two manure application management systems in the Jewett Brook watershed. This watershed includes some of the most intensively farmed soils/fields in the northwestern region of Vermont. Delpoyment of new technology that improves implementation of nutrient management plans and best manure application practices will maximize return on investment. This work is necessary because innovative approaches to water quality issues are needed and because the units are cost prohibitive to farmers to install on their own making grant funds are necessary. The Grantee is currently prototyping this type of work under an earlier 2013 ERP grant. The two systems combine data logging, GIS and GPS technology. This system will allow for the identification of environmentally sensitive areas such as wells for drinking water purposes, grassed waterways, ditches, buffers and standpipes and prevent application of manure in these areas. This system will also provide a way for the producer to adhere to the nutrient application recommendations in their Nutrient Management Plan. Project is considered to constitute a watershed based plan implementation effort in light of Northern Lake Champlain basin plan (2015) and BMP scenario tool associated with Lake Champlain TMDL being developed by EPA-Region 1.

project_info.prj_title: Reduction of Fall Tillage in Jewett Brook/Stevens Brook Watersheds
project_info.prj_overview: Project will introduce and demonstrate new equipment which, when coupled with existing NRCS programs, will enable farmers to substantially reduce erosion and improve soil health in two watersheds of the St. Albans Bay watershed. Currently, the farming practices of this area involve fall tillage of the clay soils to prevent problems of "balling" of the clay during spring tillage operations. Because of the severe potential for drastic yield reductions from spring tillage, farmers are very hesitant to change practices. This grant will introduce a new low impact system for developing improved soil health on clay soils. This system is being implemented in other areas of the country as well as a few farms in Vermont with heavy clay soils. This system will involve use of a no-till deep ripper to remove compaction (a very common problem in high clay content soils) with minimal surface disturbance in the fall after corn harvest. The new system requires: subsoiling (to 18 inch depth) with cover crops and no other fall tillage; light manure application in the spring with shallow cover crop and manure incoporation with Kelly Disc Harrow. Project involves purchasing a DMI 2500 subsoiler to perform this task. This subsoiler is capable of breaking up soil compaction up to 24 inches deep without disturbing the surface of the soil. It uses very slender shanks with no-till tips to accomplish this. This equipment will be coupled with the introduction (with NRCS assistance) of using cover crops on these fields which is not currently being implemented due to the need to fall till these soils and the lack of time required after tillage to get an adequate cover crop established. In the spring, Grantee will introduce farmers to a Kelly Disc Harrow which lightly works the top 1-2 inches of soil enough to get a nice seed bed established for planting the cash crop. Grantee's intention is to implement this practice (ie fall subsoiler followed by cover crops then spring Kelly Disc Harrow) on 10 farms totaling at least 500 acres in these two targeted watersheds over the lifespan of this grant. Project is considered to constitute a watershed based plan implementation effort in light of Northern Lake Champlain basin plan (2015) and BMP scenario tool associated with Lake Champlain TMDL being developed by EPA-Region 1.

Project is considered to constitute a watershed based plan implementation effort in light of Winooski River basin plan (2012) and BMP scenario tool associated with Lake Champlain TMDL being developed by EPA-Region 1.

The new and enhanced street sweeper technology will be used to clean sediment/debris from 48 miles of city streets and municipal parking lots, preventing sediment and nutrient pollution from entering the Stevens Branch of the Winooski River.

project_info.prj_title: Lake Iroqouis Streambed Restoration and Erosion Control
project_info.prj_overview: This project involves implementation of practices to reduce flow, erosion, sedimentation, and channelization near Pine Shore Road and Lake Iroquois in Hinesburg, VT. Construction of roadside erosion control practices, including crowning, grading, turnouts, and reshaped/improved drainage ditches, along Pine Shore Road will dissipate road-runoff and allow infiltration into an adjacent vegetated area. The second component is retrofitting an existing stormwater retention pond, treating runoff from Pine Shore Road, to further reduce stormwater velocity and suspended sediment. The retrofit will also involve replacing the overflow pipe with a rock-lined overspill and splash zone that will allow the pond to capture more sediment, prevent future erosion during overflows, and repair existing erosion issues caused by the overflow pipe. Finally, this project involves reshaping a stormwater conveyance draining into Lake Iroquois with a series of stone weirs to fix an eroding head-cut and reduce sediment load.

project_info.prj_title: Wolcott Town Garage and Fire Station Stormwater Management Improvements
project_info.prj_overview: This project is located at the Wolcott Town Garage and Fire Department shared facility near the Lamoille River. The 2016 Lamoille Tactical Basin Plan identifies this section of the Lamoille River as "altered" and "stressed" due to sediment, turbidity, and erosion. The project addresses roof runoff that carries sediment and nutrients from the parking area and discharges in the Lamoille River. The project involves disconnecting roof runoff and installing infiltration practices to reduce runoff and sediment and nutrient loading to the Lamoille River. The project also involves installation of concrete retaining walls to confine the sand pile and protect it from runoff that would carry sand to the Lamoille River. Finally, road erosion control practices such as water bars, turnouts, and settling pools will be installed along the work road and staging area to prevent future erosion and sediment loading.

project_info.prj_title: Bioretention at Harwood Union Middle/High School
project_info.prj_overview: This project involves construction of a bioretention practice at Harwood Union School. The grantee will construct a 1,400 square-foot bioretention practice that will mitigate runoff from approximately 0.53 acres of rooftop runoff that collects in roof drains and empties into a pipe system that outlets in Lozelle Brook. The bioretention practice will be planted with native plants. This project aims to manage stormwater and pollutants by restoring the natural hydrology in the subwatershed. With the incorporation of several green stormwater infrastructure (GSI) practices, this project will reduce runoff and pollutant loading as close to the source as possible, before it reaches Lozelle and Dowsville Brooks. This project, located outside the middle schools science wing, will also be used as an outdoor classroom to educate students on bioretention practices.

project_info.prj_title: Enhancing the Water Quality Benefit of Cover Crops
project_info.prj_overview: This grant was awarded to University of Vermont (UVM) Extension to further investigate and demonstrate the water quality benefits of cover crops. The project involves purchasing and installing two cover crop crimper units, which mount directly to corn planters to flatten and terminate cover crop while planting corn in no-till systems. This project also involves purchasing and demonstrating the Dawn Manufacturing DuoSeeder. The DuoSeeder improves establishment of cover crop by allowing planting of cover crops in soil between rows of corn, rather than broadcasting seed into growing corn. The goal is to plant cover crops early during corn development to establish a living mulch between the rows of corn and provide soil protection throughout the growing season, resulting in healthier soils and reduced pollution from agricultural runoff. The tools will be demonstrated on at least 12 farms and/or 1,200 acres located in the Missisquoi Bay Watershed.

project_info.prj_overview: This project involves construction of a series of stormwater treatment practices in the densely developed Park-Winter Meadow neighborhood in the City of Barre. The project will minimize stormwater runoff to Edgewood Brook and the Stevens Branch two highly urbanized streams susceptible to stormwater stressors. Stormwater treatment practices include a series of vegetated swales to intercept and treat runoff, as well as an underground infiltration chamber receiving stormwater from the citys catch basin system. Additionally, road erosion control practices including grading and installation of a drainage swale will be installed to minimize erosion and sediment. These practices, combined, will treat stormwater runoff from 0.6 impervious acres and improve 520 feet of road drainage, reducing 4.5 pounds of total phosphorus loading and 4,550 pounds of sediment loading annually (consultant-provided estimate, to be verified).

This project involves construction of a stormwater treatment practice at the intersection of Water Street and Union Brook in Northfield. project_info.prj_overview: The Johnson State College (JSC) Stormwater Improvement Project will capture, retain, and treat the stormwater flow from more than 3 impervious acres and improve flood resiliency on campus. The project involves routing additional stormwater to an existing stormwater retention pond by installing a conveyance system and hydrodynamic separator. These retrofits to the existing pond are estimated to treat an additional 0.83 pounds of phosphorus and 1,064 pounds of sediment from receiving waters, annually (consultant-provided estimate, to be verified), and reduce flow to improve flood resiliency of receiving waters. Additionally, a small green stormwater infrastructure/public demonstration practice will be installed to capture and infiltrate runoff from nearby athletic fields.
